  <span id="freeText11654991763622058344" style="display:none"><i> I pushed the cabinet over and it made a loud crash followed by little tinkling sounds. I love that sound. My ancestors must’ve been Vandals or Visigoths or something.</i><br /><br />John Corey is the ultimate wise-ass with top tier dad jokes-very similar to Paul Brenner, another one of DeMille’s main characters. This book starts with Corey recuperating from a gunshot wound in his uncle’s house on the North Fork of Long Island-a rural area far from the city. In fact, this book did a pretty good job of making Long Island sound way more appealing than I had ever dreamed possible, but I digress. Corey gets sucked in, unwillingly at first, into the murder investigation of two acquaintances of his that live nearby. It turns out they work on Plum Island-officially an animal disease research center, but it’s suspected they’re actually researching much more. The big question-did their jobs have anything to do with their deaths? <br /><br />Nelson DeMille books are fun to read. I’m discovering that I enjoy reading them more then I’d even like to admit. This book was no exception, and I look forward to reading more. His writing is actually quite capable and entertaining. The truth is, this book could likely have been trimmed down-it’s true that this story didn’t need 600 pages to be told, yet I was never bored. I was also pleasantly surprised at all the history of the area that was included here.<br /><br />We got quite a few unexpected twists and turns here, some of which I never would have seen coming-no Kidding! The dialogue is good and indeed I laughed out loud more than once while reading this. The humor is present throughout, even during the more tense scenes which may rub some people the wrong way, but I enjoyed it. <br /><br />Overall, this certainly isn’t high literature or anything, but it was a blast to read, and very difficult to put down. It was a solid mystery book, and I’ll definitely be checking out the next book in the series. <br /><br />Oh and yes, John Corey is a complete pig. So if that will bother you, you may want to give this one a miss. <br /><br />3.8/5</span>
